1. Managed Tables (Built-in Automation)
When creating a standard table inside Databricks Unity Catalog without assigning a custom cloud path, Databricks assumes full ownership of both the metadata and the physical data files. Because Databricks has direct, pre-authenticated control over its central managed storage bucket, it proactively executes file-system-level actions during compilation.
Who creates the _delta_log? Databricks Unity Catalog creates it. During the CREATE TABLE compilation phase, Unity Catalog connects to its internal storage bucket, sets up the physical table directory, and explicitly writes the _delta_log folder along with its first transaction file (00000000000000000000.json). It initializes a valid Delta transaction commit history (Version 0), which allows metadata inspection commands like DESCRIBE HISTORY to succeed immediately.

2. External Tables (Hands-off Pointer Declaration)
When adding a custom cloud path via the LOCATION 'gs://your-bucket/path/' clause, the table transitions into an External Table. From an architectural standpoint, a CREATE TABLE statement for an external entity acts exclusively as a logical mapping operation within the Metastore.
Who creates the _delta_log? The data operations themselves (INSERT, MERGE, COPY INTO, or path-based Python data frame writes) create it. Unity Catalog completely stays out of your cloud storage bucket during creation. Delta Lake defers the physical creation of files and the structural _delta_log transaction framework entirely to the Write Layer (The Operations).
The Result: Because Unity Catalog doesn't touch the cloud bucket, checking the status or history of a newly registered external table prior to executing a data pipeline payload/operation will result in a file-system missing transaction log exception (DELTA_PATH_DOES_NOT_EXIST / DELTA_MISSING_TRANSACTION_LOG) because the _delta_log folder literally does not exist yet.

Why this happens: Unity Catalog vs. Cloud Storage Boundary
The root cause of this difference comes down to ownership boundaries: Databricks Unity Catalog is an independent software layer; it is not a native part of GCP, AWS, or Azure. * When you use a Managed Table, Unity Catalog handles everything within its own walled garden (the storage bucket Databricks set up for you during deployment). It has full permission to write files there the second you hit run.
When you create an External Table, you are pointing Databricks toward a third-party cloud environment (like your company's private GCS bucket). Because Unity Catalog is an external service relative to your cloud network, its CREATE TABLE command acts purely as a logical placeholder in the metastore registry. It intentionally stays out of your cloud storage bucket during creation.
Because Unity Catalog does not cross that boundary to set up your directory layout, the physical _delta_log folder is left uncreated. The onus shifts completely to the user to manually trigger its creation by running an initial operation—such as an INSERT, UPDATE, MERGE, DELETE, or an empty DataFrame write—which forces the Spark execution engine to log the transaction on your cloud bucket for the very first time.
